Marginal cost: the cost that the buyer is willing to pay for an extra of an item

Trade makes everyone better off

Concepts: Opportunity cost, marginalalism and Efficient markets

Opportunity costs represent the potential benefits an individual, investor, or business misses out on when choosing one alternative over another.

Markets are usually a good way to organise economic activiy

Adam Smith

Market failure occurs when the market fails to allocate resources efficiently

Externalities: actions of one party affects another party, but has no effect on the party itself. Eg: factories dumping waste into the river and the fishermen which are affected by it.

Information asymmetry: nformation asymmetry deals with the study of decisions in transactions where one party has more or better information than the other.
	The party having more knowledge about some product always commands the market value
	Eg: Lemon is poorly performing, but lemonade is high performing 
	
A country's standard of living ?

Prices rise when the government prints too much money

Society faces a short-run trade-off between inflation and unemployment (Philips curve)
	Prices are inversely proportional to unemployment
	
Efficient markets: Any opportunity of profit is overcome almost immediately

Ceteris paribus: a device used to analyse the relationship between 2 variables if other variables are kept constant. it is one part of the process of abstraction

The Post Hoc fallacy: if A happened before B, then It isnt necessary that A caused B

Growth: An increase in the total output of the nation
Stability: he economy growing stably, and there is full employment of resources
